        "description": "For MRL 2, Numerical code verification requires Gradation 1: confirmation that the solver is verified via published benchmark or order-of-accuracy tests. Gradation 2 additionally requires project-specific manufactured solution verification."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "rationale": "A three-level GCI study was performed on the shear-stress-weighted exposure time integral, the primary QoI for hemolysis prediction. The fine-to-medium GCI is 9.4%, exceeding the Gradation 2 threshold of ≤5% required for MRL 2. Only a single-level Richardson extrapolation with no systematic convergence demonstration was completed for the coarser grids, meeting only Gradation 1. Computational resource constraints prevented generation of a sufficiently refined mesh to achieve convergence within the required tolerance. This shortfall directly undermines confidence in the hemolysis index predictions and is a primary basis for the Not accepted decision.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/disc-error-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "For MRL 2, Discretization error requires Gradation 2: a systematic grid convergence study (GCI or equivalent) demonstrating that discretization-induced uncertainty in the primary QoI is ≤5% of the mean predicted value at the fine grid level, with monotonic convergence confirmed across at least three grid levels."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, rotational speed, blood analog viscosity, temperature) are documented with calibrated instrumentation traceable to NIST standards. Operating points span the COU envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Uncertainty in inlet boundary conditions propagated to simulation inputs. Gradation 2 achieved.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/test-conditions-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "For MRL 2, Test conditions requires Gradation 2: all experimental boundary conditions are documented with calibrated, traceable instrumentation; operating points cover the COU envelope; and boundary condition uncertainty is characterized and propagated to simulation inputs."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH and pump head are compared against experimental measurements using both absolute error metrics and a validation uncertainty analysis per ASME V&V 20. The comparison metric (E = D − S) is computed for all five operating points with combined experimental and numerical uncertainty bands reported. Gradation 2 achieved.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/output-comparison-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "For MRL 2, Output comparison requires Gradation 2: quantitative comparison of simulation outputs against experimental data using a defined metric, with combined uncertainty (experimental plus numerical) reported for each operating point."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "The primary QoI (NIH and relative hemolysis index RH) are directly mapped to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate device). A formal QoI traceability matrix links each simulation output to the COU decision question. Sensitivity of the acceptance decision to QoI selection was assessed via surrogate model. Gradation 3 achieved against Gradation 2 requirement.",
