        "description": "For MRL 2, Relevance of the quantities of interest requires Gradation 2: QoIs are explicitly linked to the COU decision question with documented justification. Gradation 3 additionally requires a formal traceability matrix and sensitivity analysis of the decision to QoI selection."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "Validation experiments use the same FDA generic pump geometry as the COU simulations. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water, matched viscosity) replicates in-vivo rheology within documented tolerance. Operating conditions overlap the COU envelope. Validation domain is judged sufficiently representative of the COU for MRL 2. Gradation 2 achieved.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/val-relevance-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "For MRL 2, Relevance of the validation activities to the COU requires Gradation 2: the validation geometry, fluid properties, and operating conditions are documented to be representative of the COU, with any discrepancies between validation and COU conditions identified and assessed for impact."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error (iterative convergence and round-off) is scoped out at MRL 2 for this assessment because the commercially validated solver enforces residual convergence to 10^-6 for all transport equations by default, and double-precision arithmetic eliminates round-off as a meaningful contributor relative to discretization error. A separate solver-level verification report (ANSYS, 2022) documents iterative and round-off error bounds applicable to this solver configuration. Re-assessment would be triggered if a custom solver or reduced-precision configuration were adopted."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out at MRL 2 because the simulation workflow is executed by a single experienced CFD analyst under a documented simulation plan with independent peer review of boundary condition setup and post-processing scripts. The risk of consequential user error is judged low relative to the dominant uncertainty sources (discretization and model form). Formal use-error assessment would be required if the workflow were transferred to a different operator or automated without peer review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "rationale": "The hemolysis power-law model (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) is applied without modification to the CFD shear field. A literature review identified that the model was calibrated on Couette-flow data and exhibits systematic under-prediction of NIH in recirculation-dominated flows, which are present in the CPB pump at low-flow operating points. No alternative model form was evaluated and no correction factor was applied. Only a qualitative discussion of model-form uncertainty is provided (Gradation 1); a quantitative model-form error estimate using an alternative hemolysis model or data-driven correction (required for Gradation 2 at MRL 2) was not completed. This shortfall, combined with the discretization error shortfall, is a co-primary basis for the Not accepted decision.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-form-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "For MRL 2, Model form requires Gradation 2: a quantitative estimate of model-form error or uncertainty is provided, either through comparison of alternative constitutive models or through a data-driven error characterization, with the estimate propagated to the primary QoI."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "All simulation input parameters (geometry dimensions, fluid properties, rotational speed, inlet flow profiles) are documented with sources and uncertainty ranges. A one-at-a-time sensitivity study quantified the influence of each uncertain input on predicted NIH. Blood viscosity and inlet velocity profile are identified as the dominant uncertain inputs; their uncertainty is propagated via Monte Carlo to the QoI. Gradation 2 achieved.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/model-inputs-mrl2",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "For MRL 2, Model inputs requires Gradation 2: all uncertain inputs are identified and characterized with uncertainty ranges; a sensitivity study identifies dominant inputs; and uncertainty in dominant inputs is propagated to the primary QoI."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test samples is scoped out because the validation dataset uses a blood analog (glycerol-water mixture) rather than biological blood samples, eliminating donor-to-donor biological variability as a factor. The rheological properties of the analog are fully characterized by the manufacturer's specification sheet and confirmed by in-house viscometry. Sample-to-sample variability in the analog is negligible relative to other uncertainty sources. This scoping decision is consistent with FDA guidance on the use of blood analogs for in-vitro pump hemolysis testing."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is scoped out because the validation experiment and the COU simulation use identical pump geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump CAD model) and the same nominal operating conditions. No geometric scaling or operating-condition extrapolation is performed between the validation domain and the COU. Any minor manufacturing tolerance variation in the physical test article relative to the CAD model is documented and assessed as having negligible impact on the hemolysis index at MRL 2."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/cpb-cou1-not-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/morrison-credibility-lead",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team lead",
    "outcome": "Not accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for COU1 (CFD hemolysis prediction for CPB Class II device, MRL 2) is Not accepted on the basis of two co-primary factor shortfalls, neither of which is offset by compensating evidence. First, the Discretization error factor achieves only Gradation 1 against a required Gradation 2: the GCI on the fine-to-medium grid transition is 9.4% for the shear-stress-weighted exposure time integral, nearly double the ≤5% threshold. The inability to demonstrate grid-converged hemolysis predictions means that the primary QoI (NIH, RH) carries unquantified discretization-induced bias of unknown sign and magnitude. Second, the Model form factor achieves only Gradation 1 against a required Gradation 2: the Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model is applied without quantitative model-form error characterization despite documented literature evidence of systematic under-prediction in recirculation-dominated flows present at low-flow operating points. Together, these two shortfalls mean that the simulation cannot reliably bound worst-case hemolysis across the COU operating envelope. The validation comparison (mean NIH error 18.3%) is consistent with both shortfalls contributing to prediction bias. No offset rationale is claimed: the team judges that the combined effect of unquantified discretization and model-form error is material to the regulatory decision (RH < 1 criterion) and cannot be dismissed without additional evidence. Remediation path: (1) generate a mesh with GCI ≤ 5% on the hemolysis integral QoI; (2) evaluate at least one alternative hemolysis constitutive model and quantify model-form uncertainty. Re-submission is recommended following completion of both remediation activities.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
